<div class="question" id="question-3">
                    <h3>Question 3</h3>
                    <div class="question-content">
                        <p>Using the quadratic formula, solve the equation \(y-6y-27=0\).</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="answer-section">
                        <h4>Answer</h4>
                        <div class="answer-content" id="answer-3">
                            <div class="answer-detail">
                                <div class="step-by-step">
                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>First, rearrange to standard form \(ay^2 + by + c = 0\):</p>
                                        <p>\[y-6y-27=0\]</p>
                                        <p>\[(1)y-6y-27=0\]</p>
                                        <p>\[y^2-6y-27=0\]</p>
                                    </div>
                                    
                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Identify the coefficients:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>\(a = 1\)</li>
                                            <li>\(b = -6\)</li>
                                            <li>\(c = -27\)</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>

                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Use the quadratic formula: \[y = \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}\]</p>
                                        <p>Substitute the values:</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{-(-6) \pm \sqrt{(-6)^2-4(1)(-27)}}{2(1)}\]</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{6 \pm \sqrt{36+108}}{2}\]</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{6 \pm \sqrt{144}}{2}\]</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{6 \pm 12}{2}\]</p>
                                    </div>

                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Solve for both values:</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{6 + 12}{2} = \frac{18}{2} = 9\]</p>
                                        <p>\[y = \frac{6 - 12}{2} = \frac{-6}{2} = -3\]</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                
                                <p class="answer-conclusion">Therefore, the solutions are \(y = 9\) or \(y = -3\)</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="question" id="question-4">
                    <h3>Question 4</h3>
                    <div class="question-content">
                        <p>Use the binomial theorem to expand the expression \((3x-2)^4\)</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="answer-section">
                        <h4>Answer</h4>
                        <div class="answer-content" id="answer-4">
                            <div class="answer-detail">
                                <p>Using the binomial theorem:</p>
                                <p>\[(a+b)^n = \sum_{r=0}^n \binom{n}{r} a^{n-r} b^r\]</p>
                                
                                <div class="step-by-step">
                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Here, we have:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>\(a = 3x\)</li>
                                            <li>\(b = -2\)</li>
                                            <li>\(n = 4\)</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                    
                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Calculate binomial coefficients \(\binom{4}{r}\) for r = 0 to 4:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li>\(\binom{4}{0} = 1\)</li>
                                            <li>\(\binom{4}{1} = 4\)</li>
                                            <li>\(\binom{4}{2} = 6\)</li>
                                            <li>\(\binom{4}{3} = 4\)</li>
                                            <li>\(\binom{4}{4} = 1\)</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                    
                                    <div class="step">
                                        <p>Expand term by term:</p>
                                        <p>\(\binom{4}{0}(3x)^4(-2)^0 = 81x^4\)</p>
                                        <p>\(\binom{4}{1}(3x)^3(-2)^1 = -216x^3\)</p>
                                        <p>\(\binom{4}{2}(3x)^2(-2)^2 = 216x^2\)</p>
                                        <p>\(\binom{4}{3}(3x)^1(-2)^3 = -96x\)</p>
                                        <p>\(\binom{4}{4}(3x)^0(-2)^4 = 16\)</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                
                                <p class="answer-conclusion">Therefore, \((3x-2)^4 = 81x^4 - 216x^3 + 216x^2 - 96x + 16\)</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="question" id="question-5">
                    <h3>Question 5</h3>
                    <div class="question-content">
                        <p>Describe each of the following types of matrices:</p>
                        <p>(a) identity matrix;</p>
                        <p>(b) singular matrix.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="answer-section">
                        <h4>Answer</h4>
                        <div class="answer-content" id="answer-5">
                            <div class="answer-detail">
                                <p><strong>(a) Identity Matrix:</strong></p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>A square matrix where all diagonal elements are 1 and all other elements are 0</li>
                                    <li>Usually denoted as \(I\) or \(I_n\) where n is the size of the matrix</li>
                                    <li>Example of a 3×3 identity matrix:</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p>\[I_3 = \begin{bmatrix}
                                1 & 0 & 0 \\
                                0 & 1 & 0 \\
                                0 & 0 & 1
                                \end{bmatrix}\]</p>
                                <p>Properties:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>For any matrix A, \(AI = IA = A\)</li>
                                    <li>Its determinant is always 1</li>
                                    <li>It is symmetric: \(I = I^T\)</li>
                                </ul>

                                <p><strong>(b) Singular Matrix:</strong></p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>A square matrix whose determinant is zero</li>
                                    <li>This means it does not have an inverse</li>
                                    <li>The columns (or rows) are linearly dependent</li>
                                    <li>Example of a singular matrix:</li>
                                </ul>
                                <p>\[\begin{bmatrix}
                                2 & 4 \\
                                1 & 2
                                \end{bmatrix}\]</p>
                                <p>Properties:</p>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>The matrix equation \(Ax = 0\) has non-trivial solutions</li>
                                    <li>At least one row or column can be expressed as a linear combination of others</li>
                                    <li>The system of equations represented by a singular matrix has either no solution or infinitely many solutions</li>
                                </ul>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
